        <marginalia hand="English_secretary">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="right_margin" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Dicit loca quadrata lun[a]e, no[n] cu[m] &Moon; ip[s]a dichotomos fuerit, sed quomodocu[m]q[ue] ip[s]a fuerit, aspectus
                    quadratos in [quo] p[..]ta cada[n]t, observare monet, vt cu[m] &Moon; ibid[em] fuerit figura exacte erigatur.</marginalia_text> <!--JG: Can't figure out the word before cadant--> 
                    <!-- FSF: I think there is a comma after Dicit; could it be: in que pu[n]cta cada[n]t? -->
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>He says that there [are] quadruple place of the moon, not when the moon itself was cut in two, but whenever it was, the guadruple aspects
            in which the [....] fall, he admonishes to observe, so that the moon would be raised when it exactly was the same figure.</translation> <!--JG: Extremely unsure-->
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="English_secretary">
            <language ident="LA">
